On Escalation Ticket # 00419503 the new comment has been added: Carla Whiteford:

@Salesforce The next time the customer faces this issue, could they run the following SQL query and send us the results. We need to check the number of open connections in the background, as we think there could be an issue there. Thanks.


--- CODE ---
SELECT

    c.session_id,
    s.login_name,
    c.connect_time,
    s.host_name,
    s.program_name,
    s.status
FROM
    sys.dm_exec_connections AS c
JOIN
    sys.dm_exec_sessions AS s
ON
    c.session_id = s.session_id;
--- CODE ---

On Escalation Ticket # 00419503 the new comment has been added: Carla Whiteford:

@Salesforce Hi Damir! Could you please ask the customer to provide a process dump (as per these instructions https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/z-kb-articles-salesforce/page/kA04u0000000J03CAE.html), making use of procdump -ma PID

where PID is the process ID in question (e.g. for PID 12345 they'll do procdump -ma 12345 at an administrator command prompt), and to do it for a sampling of the running StealthAUDIT.exe processes. For example, if they expect to have 5 jobs running, they should take dumps of more than 5 processes. They should also take some screenshots of the "Running Instances" node in the job tree of the console. It will be most useful if they perform this next time they see the issue.
When they perform this action, it would be handy to get fresh log files from the StealthAUDITSADatabaseLogs folder (from both the Application and SAJobEngine subfolders), as they'll be of use alongside the dump files.
